Secretary of the Interior Ken Salazar, joined by New York Sen. Chuck Schumer, announced the re-opening plans today.

'Hurricane Sandy inflicted major 
damage on facilities that support the Statue of Liberty,' Salazar said. 
'Based on the tremendous progress we have made, Lady Liberty will be 
open to the public in time for the July 4th celebration.'

As much as three-fourths of Liberty 
Island's 12 acres was flooded, officials estimated, with water reaching 
as high as eight feet. The rest of New York Harbor was greatly damaged 
as well.

Sandy came one day after the Statue of
Liberty's 126th birthday and the reopening of the crown, which had been
closed for a year for a $30 million upgrade to fire alarms, sprinkler 
systems and exit routes.

